text.text: Bubbles on a Budget

Oscar Wilde once said, 'Pleasure without Champagne is purely artificial.' But as much as we admire the man's hedonistic spirit, we sadly don't have the funds to afford his way of life, and tend to quaff the less prestigious bubbles instead. 

Having said that, there's plenty of good fizz to be had in London, without the associated price tag. Prosecco, cava and cremant all seem to give us the same frothy festive feels. Hoorah.
Cremant

Made with the same painfully long traditional method as Champagne (méthode traditionelle), Cremant is really just as finessed as the real deal. You just can't call it champers cause it ain't from the Champagne region - so you can't charge as much either. Happy days.

tip.text:
***Permanently Closed***

This wine bar and restaurant is bringing a little bit of Dalston to, er, Haggerston. The wine-focused neighbourhood dining is a tried and tested formula, and we're still rating it. Sapling keeps things classy with pale tiles, a big communal table in the centre and booth seating lining the walls - ideal for a romantic rendez-vous.

Dishes are of the sexy bistro style that London has come to love - think Scottish langoustines with carrot butter; pork terrine with white grape and watercress; or hake with a cockle and potato sauce and a prerequisite sprinkling of monks beard. It's a resto designed for sharing with boo: you'll likely share a bottle of something biodynamic, some small plates, a medjool date pudding and then a cheeky snog.

text.text: The wine-focused neighbourhood dining is a tried and tested formula, hence why Sapling's bistro style small plates, fine wine list and booth seating make it the perfect spot romantic rendez-vous. A glass of Cremant here comes in at £7.45. Not the cheapest bubbles about but still v manageable, wouldn't you say?

tip.text: Probably the original spot for a date, this is the oldest wine bar in London with a reputation for excellent cheese platters and an incredible selection of wines to sample. But the best part is simply the candle-lit cellar setting. Go to do a little romancing here and let us know how it goes. But if it all goes terribly, we had no part in any of it. Oh, and it gets super busy on weekends so get down there early.

text.text: Probably the original spot for a date, this is the oldest wine bar in London with a reputation for excellent cheese platters and an incredible selection of vinos. Get there early to nab a seat in the candlelit cellar and indulge in fizz of the prosecco, cava or cremant variety. Their fave is a Brut de Blanc at £7.70 a glass.

tip.text:
Soif is a buzzing French bistro where the focus is on expertly chosen wine, independently-sourced food and the French art of nattering. Rather than mass produced tipples, you can look forward to their Monday evening tastings featuring high-class wines at cheaper prices.

Food-wise, the steak tartare is dreamy and you can't really go wrong with their set lunch menu for a tenner. Also, it's BYOB on Mondays (no corkage) so you can get down and dirty on the cheap.

text.text: Soif is a buzzing French bistro where the wine is expertly chosen, the food is independently-sourced and the decor is French as flip. You can't really go wrong with their set lunch menu for a tenner, which allows a little more wallet room for their cremant by the bottle.
Cava

Cava is the Spanish equivalent also made with the old-school, yeast-heavy champagne method. Imported from Spain where life is apparently cheaper, cava by the glass is mucho affordable coming in at £5 in some places and up to £7.50 in others.

tip.text:
The pigs with the power up at Jamon Y Salud (one of Spain's top jamón ibérico producers) had the bright idea of opening a tapas bar in Islington; and we think they're onto something. You know jamón ibérico right? The one where the pigs eat acorns so they're extra tasty. Well Llerena is filled with the stuff. Platters of cured meats, creamy cheeses and vino tinto... Where do we sign?

There's also a tapas menu featuring all the classics. You know the ones, you went to that festival in Spain once. The fine wine, Estrella, sherry and cava should remind you of your holibobs, too. And the churros. Tick, tick, tick.

text.text: You know jamón ibérico right? The one where the pigs eat acorns so they're extra tasty. Well Llerena is filled with the stuff. Platters of cured meats, creamy cheeses and vino... Where do we sign? If that doesn't tempt ya their £5 cava should, eh?

tip.text:
'Vermouth is coming,' we keep hearing. If this buzzing Nunhead spot is anything to go by, it can't happen soon enough. Set up by brother and sister Ollie and Greta, this honestly feels like a trip to an atmospheric taberna in Barcelona or Madrid. Where you can sit up at the bar chirpsing and chewing the fat, or take things to the tables in the back and fall under the heady spell of jivin' Spanish rhythms, beautifully botanical vermouth and indulgent cheeses and meats.

The level of detail here had us forgetting all about the Nunhead strip outside: from the huge wooden wine barrels acting as tables, to the authentic vintage paintings and wall hangings, the heritage deep-red wallpaper and, lest forgetting, an impressive collection of vermouths. Whilst they do Spanish wines, beers and cocktails, you really ought to try at least one glass - we suggest asking the bar staff for a recommendation. When this place fills on weekend evenings, it gets lively enough to fill you with that alluring foreign feeling that anything is possible, striking up convos with whoever is around and eating as much manchego as your body will allow. A damn nice vermouth vacation.

text.text: Set up by brother and sister Ollie and Greta, this Nunhead spot feels like a trip to an atmospheric taberna in Barcelona or Madrid. El Vermut imports all their bubbles from Barcelona and has a total of six cavas by the glass, some white and some rosé; and all between £4.20 and £5.50. Tidy.

tip.text:
Tapas is one of the most social eating styles about, so you can see why people are fond of it. After knocking out some quality taps at Pop Brixton, Donostia Social Club has fled to another culinary melting pot: Tooting Broadway market.

Nibble on grilled white asparagus with romesco and toasted almonds, then dive into cheese and charcuterie boards. Sip on wine, sherry and cava from Spain and the Basque region or go real authentic and go for the prime tapas partner - a Galician vermouth (sweet, zesty or smokey, depending on your preference).

text.text: After knocking out some quality tapas at Pop Brixton, Donostia Social Club renamed themselves and fled to another culinary melting pot: Tooting Broadway market. First order, a glass of cava for £6.50 then something sultry like grilled white asparagus with romesco and toasted almonds, or indulgent cheese and charcuterie boards.
Prosecco

Still a sparkling white wine, Prosecco isn't made in the same way as champers: it's aged for a much shorter time making it younger, and (generally) sweeter than the French stuff. It's bubbles are lighter too as it's aged a lower pressure; but most importantly, it's still not nearly as pricey.

tip.text:
The idea behind this place was to create the vibe of a family-run trattoria found in Northern Italy. And, whilst we don't have that much evidence to compare to, we reckon they've done a pretty fine job. Serving up Italian food, sharing plates and homemade vermouth in a warm, well-lit basement, this place is a good bet for a special meal or just grabbing some cocktails after work.

The decor is full of subtle, tasteful nods to Italy and adds a nice bit of authenticity. We'd recommend taking a seat at their brass vermouth counter where an array of exotic ingredients sit in front of you and ordering yourself one of their classic Negronis (or go rogue and choose your own combos). The menu is full of pasta, meat and fish - and the Deep Fried Squid is certainly our pick of it. It's not a cheap place but this is Soho after all - and the atmosphere alone means it's worth shelling out a little extra.

text.text: Serving up Italian food, sharing plates and homemade vermouth in a warm, well-lit basement, this place is a good bet for a special meal or just grabbing some cocktails after work. Their food is bang on the money, but does add up so save your pennies on prosecco (£6.50) or frizzante (£5.50).

tip.text:
We may not be the savviest wine connoisseurs but there's no way we'd let that stand in the way of the beauty that is Sager + Wilde. This fine wine bar nestled on Hackney Road just ooooozes cool. Whichever vino it is you fancy - full-bodied, crisp and dry, fruity, a dash of sparkle - they'll take the time get to know your flavour.

Perfect to impress on date nights, mate nights, solo tipple nights... we ain't judging. Make sure to grab a small plate or cheese board for starters. Later when the wine's flowing freely, hit up the grilled cheese.

text.text: Nestled on Hackney Road, this fine wine bar just ooooozes cool. Whichever vino it is you fancy - full-bodied, crisp and dry, fruity, or a dash of sparkle - they'll take the time get to know your flavour. There's actually plenty of fizz to be had here (prosecco, cava, sparkling white and rosé.)

tip.text:
The space at Polpetto is warm, tightly packed with customers and decorated with farmhouse finesse. Take a pew, prosecco in hand at the aperitivo bar or squeeze yourself among the rest of the restaurant’s fans. Polpetto is a little more intimate, a little more experimental and a little more cute than its sister Polpo restaurants - this is where all sorts of new dishes come out the open kitchen to be tested on the likes of you.

On the plate are small Italian offerings like spicy pork and fennel meatballs, swordfish tartare and Piedmontese peppers with white anchovies - it’s a grown-up concept made informal by a toe-tapping playlist and flirty offerings like the strawberry and prosecco slushie for afters. Oh and for god’s sake try the orange and Campari cake.

text.text: Polpetto is a little more intimate, a little more experimental and a little more cute than its sister Polpo restaurants - this is where all sorts of newly invented Italian wonders come out the open kitchen to be tested on the likes of you. Add prosecco for £6.50 and life is good.
Lambrusco

Even though its name is worryingly close to Lambrini, this lesser known Italian red can be very quaffable indeed. It was seen as proper trashy for a while, but it's having a bit of a moment: we've spotted it in a few high brow wine bars. Have with cheese and accept the inevitable red wine lips.

tip.text:
Wine bar with the mostest, The Drop offers a good (but not overwhelming) range of fizz, orange, rosé, white and red wine. We tried an intimidatingly cloudy orange number, then settled on a far less vinegary, far more crisp rounded and delish' pinot blanc. Cooking here is pleasantly simple, with lots of hearty British dishes coming out to play: chicken liver pâté, rarebit, pork pies, boiled ham - it's the kind of food that cries out for fine wine. We soaked ours up with a heavily buttered hake freshened up with sweet and juicy tomatoes; and the wintry flavours of a roast squash with onions, pumpkin seeds and crispy sage.

If you are living the sort of life where you can shop in the plush boutiques of Coal Drops Yard, then you really could just drop in here, at a moments notice, after luxury errands. You'd sit at high stools, under a beautiful vaulted brick ceiling and sip on a glass of something rare while knocking back oysters and belly laughs. Life, eh?

text.text: Part of the Coal Drops Yard development in King's Cross, The Drop offers a good (but not overwhelming) range of fizz, orange, rosé, white and red wine - with lots of hearty British food. Chicken liver pâté, rarebit, pork pies, boiled ham, or even oysters - it's the kind of food that cries out for a glass of something rare.

tip.text:
Just off Hoxton Square, and sporting dark wood, low lighting and the calmest of atmospheres, Via Emilia feels like a bit of a find. It specialises in the regional cooking of the Emilia-Romagna region (in Northern Italy), and is filled to the brim with goodies. You'll see some of your favourites (like the orig' spaghetti bolognese recipe registered in 1982) and some less London-friendly regional bites like the 'gnocco fritto' bread. These pillows of deep fried bread may sound odd but paired with soft white creamy cheese and quality cured meats are actually incredibly moreish.

Once you've got through those babies, turn your attention to the pasta menu, where each dish is from a different town in Northern Italy. The flavours are timeless, the pasta is homemade and the tortellini in broth will make any Italians you know from Bologna weep. So if you know one, take them, buy them a glass of Lambrusco (weird fizzy red) and tick off your good deed for the month.

text.text: Just off Hoxton Square site the calm, quiet Via Emilia. It specialises in the regional cooking of the Emilia-Romagna region (in Northern Italy), and is filled to the brim with goodies like spag bol, or the 'gnocco fritto' bread. These pillows of deep fried bread may sound odd but paired with soft white creamy cheese and quality cured meats are actually incredibly moreish.

tip.text:
Named after a cynical philosopher, Diogenes the Dog promises to help you lead a virtuous life, in accordance with nature... via coffee, pastries, snacks and quality wines.

So this rather swish looking wine bar isn't what you'd expect to find in the backstreets a short walk from Elephant and Castle station, but gentrification rages strong in these parts and so we have it... a rather nice, relatively reasonably-priced coffee and wine bar. Owner Sunny Hodge tries to import as many wines as possible directly from producers, looking for unusual bottles, with a focus on lesser known regions and small suppliers.

Grab an early morning cup of joe con cinnamon bun; or an evening sit in with your date over Italian cheese boards, cured meats or bread dipped in olive oil - yum, yum. With glasses priced between £5-14, there's some fair drinking to be had here.

text.text: This rather swish looking wine bar isn't what you'd expect to find in the backstreets behind Elephant and Castle station, but here you are. Owner Sunny Hodge tries to import as many wines as possible directly from producers, looking for unusual bottles, with a focus on lesser known regions and small suppliers. With glasses priced between £5-14, there's some fair drinking to be had here.
Wild Card

if you're willing to let fate decide for you, pop into a wee independent wine bar and see what they've got open that day. They'll usually have a fizz on the go to be drunk by the glass, and it'll usually be a little more interesting.

tip.text:
Those not on team 'wine and cheese' deserve swift, painful punishment for crimes against humanity or something. But those who are loyal to the good stuff should reward themselves with a trip to Provisions.   Pick a camp - we'll have no fence-sitters, thanks.

This faithful Holloway haunt sells all that luscious Continental grub - zingy wines by independent winemakers, perfect charcuterie boards and pungent cheeses, like gorgeous gorgonzola that we’d gladly rub all over our bodies, given the chance. There’s also regular wine tastings and a few choice wines on tap so you can BYOB (bring your own bottle) and refill it to avoid pesky bottling costs. You can then eat your goods on the spot or take ‘em all home for a little Netflix n' cheese with your loved ones.

text.text: This faithful Holloway haunt sells all that luscious Continental grub - zingy wines by independent winemakers, perfect charcuterie boards and pungent cheeses. They alternate between a bottle fermented Prosecco, with all sorts of cloudy natural flavours (at £18 a bottle) and a méthode traditionelle from France (£22 a bottle). These come in at £5-8 a glass depending on what the lads have open.

tip.text:
This wine shop-cum-restaurant has some pretty lofty peeps behind it. Laura Christie (front of house at Oklava) and her main man Chris Boustead (Boustead & Bidois), are linking arms to bring even more wine enjoyment to Highbury.

Laura has all the grape know-how, selecting a good range of wines for everyone from the guzzler to the big spender. She clearly trusts her stock, too, as you can even try before you buy! Meanwhile, Chris is cheffing up British dishes inspired by his Yorkshire roots. Warm your deepest depths with smoked beef stew and thyme dumplings, or amuse the flip out of your bouche with their mighty selection of British cheeses - because where there's good wine, there's gotta be good cheese. Right?

text.text: Linden Stores is a low key wine shop-cum-restaurant in Highbury. While Chris pumps hearty stews out the kitchen, his co-founder Laura stocks the shop with a good range of wines for everyone from the guzzler to the big spender. Pop in for dinner and drink whatever red, white and bubbly they have opened that day by the glass (for a lovely £5). When we went in they had a lovely Lemoss prosexy on.
